101 static bool darwinHasSinCos(const Triple &TT) { 0
102 assert(TT.isOSDarwin() && "should be called with darwin triple"); 0
103 // Don't bother with 32 bit x86. ----
104 if (TT.getArch() == Triple::x86) 0
105 return false; 0
106 // Macos < 10.9 has no sincos_stret. ----
107 if (TT.isMacOSX()) 0
108 return !TT.isMacOSXVersionLT(10, 9) && TT.isArch64Bit(); 0
109 // iOS < 7.0 has no sincos_stret. ----
110 if (TT.isiOS()) 0
111 return !TT.isOSVersionLT(7, 0); 0
112 // Any other darwin such as WatchOS/TvOS is new enough. ----
113 return true; 0
114 } ----

482 return UINTTOFP_I64_F32; 0
483 if (RetVT == MVT::f64) 0
484 return UINTTOFP_I64_F64; 0
485 if (RetVT == MVT::f80) 0
486 return UINTTOFP_I64_F80; 0
487 if (RetVT == MVT::f128) 0
488 return UINTTOFP_I64_F128; 0
489 if (RetVT == MVT::ppcf128) 0
490 return UINTTOFP_I64_PPCF128; 0
491 } else if (OpVT == MVT::i128) { 0
492 if (RetVT == MVT::f16) 0
493 return UINTTOFP_I128_F16; 0
494 if (RetVT == MVT::f32) 0
495 return UINTTOFP_I128_F32; 0
496 if (RetVT == MVT::f64) 0
497 return UINTTOFP_I128_F64; 0
498 if (RetVT == MVT::f80) 0
499 return UINTTOFP_I128_F80; 0
500 if (RetVT == MVT::f128) 0
501 return UINTTOFP_I128_F128; 0
502 if (RetVT == MVT::ppcf128) 0
503 return UINTTOFP_I128_PPCF128; 0
504 } ----
505 return UNKNOWN_LIBCALL; 0
506 } ----

523 RTLIB::Libcall RTLIB::getOUTLINE_ATOMIC(unsigned Opc, AtomicOrdering Order, 0
524 MVT VT) { ----
525 unsigned ModeN, ModelN; ----
526 switch (VT.SimpleTy) { 0
527 case MVT::i8: 0
528 ModeN = 0; 0
529 break; 0
530 case MVT::i16: 0
531 ModeN = 1; 0
532 break; 0
533 case MVT::i32: 0
534 ModeN = 2; 0
535 break; 0
536 case MVT::i64: 0
537 ModeN = 3; 0
538 break; 0
539 case MVT::i128: 0
540 ModeN = 4; 0
541 break; 0
542 default: 0
543 return UNKNOWN_LIBCALL; 0
544 } ----
545 ----
546 switch (Order) { 0
547 case AtomicOrdering::Monotonic: 0
548 ModelN = 0; 0
549 break; 0
550 case AtomicOrdering::Acquire: 0
551 ModelN = 1; 0
552 break; 0
553 case AtomicOrdering::Release: 0
554 ModelN = 2; 0
555 break; 0
556 case AtomicOrdering::AcquireRelease: 0
557 case AtomicOrdering::SequentiallyConsistent: ----
558 ModelN = 3; 0
559 break; 0
560 default: 0
561 return UNKNOWN_LIBCALL; 0
562 } ----
563 ----
564 #define LCALLS(A, B) \ ----
565 { A##B##_RELAX, A##B##_ACQ, A##B##_REL, A##B##_ACQ_REL } ----
566 #define LCALL5(A) \ ----
567 LCALLS(A, 1), LCALLS(A, 2), LCALLS(A, 4), LCALLS(A, 8), LCALLS(A, 16) ----
568 switch (Opc) { 0
569 case ISD::ATOMIC_CMP_SWAP: { 0
570 const Libcall LC[5][4] = {LCALL5(OUTLINE_ATOMIC_CAS)}; 0
571 return LC[ModeN][ModelN]; 0
572 } ----
573 case ISD::ATOMIC_SWAP: { 0
574 const Libcall LC[5][4] = {LCALL5(OUTLINE_ATOMIC_SWP)}; 0
575 return LC[ModeN][ModelN]; 0
576 } ----
577 case ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_ADD: { 0
578 const Libcall LC[5][4] = {LCALL5(OUTLINE_ATOMIC_LDADD)}; 0
579 return LC[ModeN][ModelN]; 0
580 } ----
581 case ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_OR: { 0
582 const Libcall LC[5][4] = {LCALL5(OUTLINE_ATOMIC_LDSET)}; 0
583 return LC[ModeN][ModelN]; 0
584 } ----
585 case ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_CLR: { 0
586 const Libcall LC[5][4] = {LCALL5(OUTLINE_ATOMIC_LDCLR)}; 0
587 return LC[ModeN][ModelN]; 0
588 } ----
589 case ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_XOR: { 0
590 const Libcall LC[5][4] = {LCALL5(OUTLINE_ATOMIC_LDEOR)}; 0
591 return LC[ModeN][ModelN]; 0
592 } ----
593 default: 0
594 return UNKNOWN_LIBCALL; 0
595 } ----
596 #undef LCALLS ----
597 #undef LCALL5 ----
598 } ----
599 ----
600 RTLIB::Libcall RTLIB::getSYNC(unsigned Opc, MVT VT) { 0
601 #define OP_TO_LIBCALL(Name, Enum) \ ----
602 case Name: \ ----
603 switch (VT.SimpleTy) { \ ----
604 default: \ ----
605 return UNKNOWN_LIBCALL; \ ----
606 case MVT::i8: \ ----
607 return Enum##_1; \ ----
608 case MVT::i16: \ ----
609 return Enum##_2; \ ----
610 case MVT::i32: \ ----
611 return Enum##_4; \ ----
612 case MVT::i64: \ ----
613 return Enum##_8; \ ----
614 case MVT::i128: \ ----
615 return Enum##_16; \ ----
616 } ----
617 ----
618 switch (Opc) { 0
619 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_SWAP, SYNC_LOCK_TEST_AND_SET) 0
620 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_CMP_SWAP, SYNC_VAL_COMPARE_AND_SWAP) 0
621 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_ADD, SYNC_FETCH_AND_ADD) 0
622 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_SUB, SYNC_FETCH_AND_SUB) 0
623 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_AND, SYNC_FETCH_AND_AND) 0
624 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_OR, SYNC_FETCH_AND_OR) 0
625 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_XOR, SYNC_FETCH_AND_XOR) 0
626 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_NAND, SYNC_FETCH_AND_NAND) 0
627 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_MAX, SYNC_FETCH_AND_MAX) 0
628 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_UMAX, SYNC_FETCH_AND_UMAX) 0
629 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_MIN, SYNC_FETCH_AND_MIN) 0
630 OP_TO_LIBCALL(ISD::ATOMIC_LOAD_UMIN, SYNC_FETCH_AND_UMIN) 0
631 } ----
632 ----
633 #undef OP_TO_LIBCALL ----
634 ----
635 return UNKNOWN_LIBCALL; 0
636 } ----

992 TargetLoweringBase::LegalizeKind ----
993 TargetLoweringBase::getTypeConversion(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT) const { 858 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
994 // If this is a simple type, use the ComputeRegisterProp mechanism. ----
995 if (VT.isSimple()) { 858 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
996 MVT SVT = VT.getSimpleVT(); 858 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
997 assert((unsigned)SVT.SimpleTy < std::size(TransformToType)); 858 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
998 MVT NVT = TransformToType[SVT.SimpleTy]; 858 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
999 LegalizeTypeAction LA = ValueTypeActions.getTypeAction(SVT); 858 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1000 ----
1001 assert((LA == TypeLegal || LA == TypeSoftenFloat || 858 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1002 LA == TypeSoftPromoteHalf || ----
1003 (NVT.isVector() || ----
1004 ValueTypeActions.getTypeAction(NVT) != TypePromoteInteger)) && ----
1005 "Promote may not follow Expand or Promote"); ----
1006 ----
1007 if (LA == TypeSplitVector) 858 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1008 return LegalizeKind(LA, EVT(SVT).getHalfNumVectorElementsVT(Context)); 0
1009 if (LA == TypeScalarizeVector) 858 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1010 return LegalizeKind(LA, SVT.getVectorElementType()); 0
1011 return LegalizeKind(LA, NVT); 858 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1012 } ----
1013 ----
1014 // Handle Extended Scalar Types. ----
1015 if (!VT.isVector()) { 0
1016 assert(VT.isInteger() && "Float types must be simple"); 0
1017 unsigned BitSize = VT.getSizeInBits(); 0
1018 // First promote to a power-of-two size, then expand if necessary. ----
1019 if (BitSize < 8 || !isPowerOf2_32(BitSize)) { 0
1020 EVT NVT = VT.getRoundIntegerType(Context); 0
1021 assert(NVT != VT && "Unable to round integer VT"); 0
1022 LegalizeKind NextStep = getTypeConversion(Context, NVT); 0
1023 // Avoid multi-step promotion. ----
1024 if (NextStep.first == TypePromoteInteger) 0
1025 return NextStep; 0
1026 // Return rounded integer type. ----
1027 return LegalizeKind(TypePromoteInteger, NVT); 0
1028 } ----
1029 ----
1030 return LegalizeKind(TypeExpandInteger, 0
1031 EVT::getIntegerVT(Context, VT.getSizeInBits() / 2)); 0
1032 } ----
1033 ----
1034 // Handle vector types. ----
1035 ElementCount NumElts = VT.getVectorElementCount(); 0
1036 EVT EltVT = VT.getVectorElementType(); 0
1037 ----
1038 // Vectors with only one element are always scalarized. ----
1039 if (NumElts.isScalar()) 0
1040 return LegalizeKind(TypeScalarizeVector, EltVT); 0
1041 ----
1042 // Try to widen vector elements until the element type is a power of two and ----
1043 // promote it to a legal type later on, for example: ----
1044 // <3 x i8> -> <4 x i8> -> <4 x i32> ----
1045 if (EltVT.isInteger()) { 0
1046 // Vectors with a number of elements that is not a power of two are always ----
1047 // widened, for example <3 x i8> -> <4 x i8>. ----
1048 if (!VT.isPow2VectorType()) { 0
1049 NumElts = NumElts.coefficientNextPowerOf2(); 0
1050 EVT NVT = EVT::getVectorVT(Context, EltVT, NumElts); 0
1051 return LegalizeKind(TypeWidenVector, NVT); 0
1052 } ----
1053 ----
1054 // Examine the element type. ----
1055 LegalizeKind LK = getTypeConversion(Context, EltVT); 0
1056 ----
1057 // If type is to be expanded, split the vector. ----
1058 // <4 x i140> -> <2 x i140> ----
1059 if (LK.first == TypeExpandInteger) { 0
1060 if (VT.getVectorElementCount().isScalable()) 0
1061 return LegalizeKind(TypeScalarizeScalableVector, EltVT); 0
1062 return LegalizeKind(TypeSplitVector, 0
1063 VT.getHalfNumVectorElementsVT(Context)); 0
1064 } ----
1065 ----
1066 // Promote the integer element types until a legal vector type is found ----
1067 // or until the element integer type is too big. If a legal type was not ----
1068 // found, fallback to the usual mechanism of widening/splitting the ----
1069 // vector. ----
1070 EVT OldEltVT = EltVT; 0
1071 while (true) { ----
1072 // Increase the bitwidth of the element to the next pow-of-two ----
1073 // (which is greater than 8 bits). ----
1074 EltVT = EVT::getIntegerVT(Context, 1 + EltVT.getSizeInBits()) 0
1075 .getRoundIntegerType(Context); 0
1076 ----
1077 // Stop trying when getting a non-simple element type. ----
1078 // Note that vector elements may be greater than legal vector element ----
1079 // types. Example: X86 XMM registers hold 64bit element on 32bit ----
1080 // systems. ----
1081 if (!EltVT.isSimple()) 0
1082 break; 0
1083 ----
1084 // Build a new vector type and check if it is legal. ----
1085 MVT NVT = MVT::getVectorVT(EltVT.getSimpleVT(), NumElts); 0
1086 // Found a legal promoted vector type. ----
1087 if (NVT != MVT() && ValueTypeActions.getTypeAction(NVT) == TypeLegal) 0
1088 return LegalizeKind(TypePromoteInteger, 0
1089 EVT::getVectorVT(Context, EltVT, NumElts)); 0
1090 } 0
1091 ----
1092 // Reset the type to the unexpanded type if we did not find a legal vector ----
1093 // type with a promoted vector element type. ----
1094 EltVT = OldEltVT; 0
1095 } ----
1096 ----
1097 // Try to widen the vector until a legal type is found. ----
1098 // If there is no wider legal type, split the vector. ----
1099 while (true) { ----
1100 // Round up to the next power of 2. ----
1101 NumElts = NumElts.coefficientNextPowerOf2(); 0
1102 ----
1103 // If there is no simple vector type with this many elements then there ----
1104 // cannot be a larger legal vector type. Note that this assumes that ----
1105 // there are no skipped intermediate vector types in the simple types. ----
1106 if (!EltVT.isSimple()) 0
1107 break; 0
1108 MVT LargerVector = MVT::getVectorVT(EltVT.getSimpleVT(), NumElts); 0
1109 if (LargerVector == MVT()) 0
1110 break; 0
1111 ----
1112 // If this type is legal then widen the vector. ----
1113 if (ValueTypeActions.getTypeAction(LargerVector) == TypeLegal) 0
1114 return LegalizeKind(TypeWidenVector, LargerVector); 0
1115 } 0
1116 ----
1117 // Widen odd vectors to next power of two. ----
1118 if (!VT.isPow2VectorType()) { 0
1119 EVT NVT = VT.getPow2VectorType(Context); 0
1120 return LegalizeKind(TypeWidenVector, NVT); 0
1121 } ----
1122 ----
1123 if (VT.getVectorElementCount() == ElementCount::getScalable(1)) 0
1124 return LegalizeKind(TypeScalarizeScalableVector, EltVT); 0
1125 ----
1126 // Vectors with illegal element types are expanded. ----
1127 EVT NVT = EVT::getVectorVT(Context, EltVT, 0
1128 VT.getVectorElementCount().divideCoefficientBy(2)); 0
1129 return LegalizeKind(TypeSplitVector, NVT); 0
1130 } ----
1131 ----
1132 static unsigned getVectorTypeBreakdownMVT(MVT VT, MVT &IntermediateVT, 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1133 unsigned &NumIntermediates, ----
1134 MVT &RegisterVT, ----
1135 TargetLoweringBase *TLI) { ----
1136 // Figure out the right, legal destination reg to copy into. ----
1137 ElementCount EC = VT.getVectorElementCount(); 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1138 MVT EltTy = VT.getVectorElementType(); 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1139 ----
1140 unsigned NumVectorRegs = 1; 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1141 ----
1142 // Scalable vectors cannot be scalarized, so splitting or widening is ----
1143 // required. ----
1144 if (VT.isScalableVector() && !isPowerOf2_32(EC.getKnownMinValue())) 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1145 llvm_unreachable( 0
1146 "Splitting or widening of non-power-of-2 MVTs is not implemented."); ----
1147 ----
1148 // FIXME: We don't support non-power-of-2-sized vectors for now. ----
1149 // Ideally we could break down into LHS/RHS like LegalizeDAG does. ----
1150 if (!isPowerOf2_32(EC.getKnownMinValue())) { 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1151 // Split EC to unit size (scalable property is preserved). ----
1152 NumVectorRegs = EC.getKnownMinValue(); 210 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1153 EC = ElementCount::getFixed(1); 210 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1154 } ----
1155 ----
1156 // Divide the input until we get to a supported size. This will ----
1157 // always end up with an EC that represent a scalar or a scalable ----
1158 // scalar. ----
1159 while (EC.getKnownMinValue() > 1 && 13790 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1160 !TLI->isTypeLegal(MVT::getVectorVT(EltTy, EC))) { 13790 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1161 EC = EC.divideCoefficientBy(2); 6040 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1162 NumVectorRegs <<= 1; 6040 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1163 } ----
1164 ----
1165 NumIntermediates = NumVectorRegs; 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1166 ----
1167 MVT NewVT = MVT::getVectorVT(EltTy, EC); 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1168 if (!TLI->isTypeLegal(NewVT)) 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1169 NewVT = EltTy; 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1170 IntermediateVT = NewVT; 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1171 ----
1172 unsigned LaneSizeInBits = NewVT.getScalarSizeInBits(); 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1173 ----
1174 // Convert sizes such as i33 to i64. ----
1175 LaneSizeInBits = llvm::bit_ceil(LaneSizeInBits); 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1176 ----
1177 MVT DestVT = TLI->getRegisterType(NewVT); 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1178 RegisterVT = DestVT; 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1179 if (EVT(DestVT).bitsLT(NewVT)) // Value is expanded, e.g. i64 -> i16. 1710 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1180 return NumVectorRegs * (LaneSizeInBits / DestVT.getScalarSizeInBits()); 198 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1181 ----
1182 // Otherwise, promotion or legal types use the same number of registers as ----
1183 // the vector decimated to the appropriate level. ----
1184 return NumVectorRegs; 1512 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1185 } ----

1196 ----
1197 /// Replace/modify any TargetFrameIndex operands with a targte-dependent ----
1198 /// sequence of memory operands that is recognized by PrologEpilogInserter. ----
1199 MachineBasicBlock * ----
1200 TargetLoweringBase::emitPatchPoint(MachineInstr &InitialMI, 0
1201 MachineBasicBlock *MBB) const { ----
1202 MachineInstr *MI = &InitialMI; 0
1203 MachineFunction &MF = *MI->getMF(); 0
1204 MachineFrameInfo &MFI = MF.getFrameInfo(); 0
1205 ----
1206 // We're handling multiple types of operands here: ----
1207 // PATCHPOINT MetaArgs - live-in, read only, direct ----
1208 // STATEPOINT Deopt Spill - live-through, read only, indirect ----
1209 // STATEPOINT Deopt Alloca - live-through, read only, direct ----
1210 // (We're currently conservative and mark the deopt slots read/write in ----
1211 // practice.) ----
1212 // STATEPOINT GC Spill - live-through, read/write, indirect ----
1213 // STATEPOINT GC Alloca - live-through, read/write, direct ----
1214 // The live-in vs live-through is handled already (the live through ones are ----
1215 // all stack slots), but we need to handle the different type of stackmap ----
1216 // operands and memory effects here. ----
1217 ----
1218 if (llvm::none_of(MI->operands(), 0
1219 [](MachineOperand &Operand) { return Operand.isFI(); })) 0
1220 return MBB; 0
1221 ----
1222 MachineInstrBuilder MIB = BuildMI(MF, MI->getDebugLoc(), MI->getDesc()); 0
1223 ----
1224 // Inherit previous memory operands. ----
1225 MIB.cloneMemRefs(*MI); 0
1226 ----
1227 for (unsigned i = 0; i < MI->getNumOperands(); ++i) { 0
1228 MachineOperand &MO = MI->getOperand(i); 0
1229 if (!MO.isFI()) { 0
1230 // Index of Def operand this Use it tied to. ----
1231 // Since Defs are coming before Uses, if Use is tied, then ----
1232 // index of Def must be smaller that index of that Use. ----
1233 // Also, Defs preserve their position in new MI. ----
1234 unsigned TiedTo = i; 0
1235 if (MO.isReg() && MO.isTied()) 0
1236 TiedTo = MI->findTiedOperandIdx(i); 0
1237 MIB.add(MO); 0
1238 if (TiedTo < i) 0
1239 MIB->tieOperands(TiedTo, MIB->getNumOperands() - 1); 0
1240 continue; 0
1241 } 0
1242 ----
1243 // foldMemoryOperand builds a new MI after replacing a single FI operand ----
1244 // with the canonical set of five x86 addressing-mode operands. ----
1245 int FI = MO.getIndex(); 0
1246 ----
1247 // Add frame index operands recognized by stackmaps.cpp ----
1248 if (MFI.isStatepointSpillSlotObjectIndex(FI)) { 0
1249 // indirect-mem-ref tag, size, #FI, offset. ----
1250 // Used for spills inserted by StatepointLowering. This codepath is not ----
1251 // used for patchpoints/stackmaps at all, for these spilling is done via ----
1252 // foldMemoryOperand callback only. ----
1253 assert(MI->getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::STATEPOINT && "sanity"); 0
1254 MIB.addImm(StackMaps::IndirectMemRefOp); 0
1255 MIB.addImm(MFI.getObjectSize(FI)); 0
1256 MIB.add(MO); 0
1257 MIB.addImm(0); 0
1258 } else { ----
1259 // direct-mem-ref tag, #FI, offset. ----
1260 // Used by patchpoint, and direct alloca arguments to statepoints ----
1261 MIB.addImm(StackMaps::DirectMemRefOp); 0
1262 MIB.add(MO); 0
1263 MIB.addImm(0); 0
1264 } ----
1265 ----
1266 assert(MIB->mayLoad() && "Folded a stackmap use to a non-load!"); 0
1267 ----
1268 // Add a new memory operand for this FI. ----

1286 /// findRepresentativeClass - Return the largest legal super-reg register class ----
1287 /// of the register class for the specified type and its associated "cost". ----
1288 // This function is in TargetLowering because it uses RegClassForVT which would ----

1293 TargetLoweringBase::findRepresentativeClass(const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI, 1980 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1294 MVT VT) const { ----
1295 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = RegClassForVT[VT.SimpleTy]; 1980 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1296 if (!RC) 1980 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll

1575 ----
1576 /// getVectorTypeBreakdown - Vector types are broken down into some number of ----
1577 /// legal first class types. For example, MVT::v8f32 maps to 2 MVT::v4f32 ----
1578 /// with Altivec or SSE1, or 8 promoted MVT::f64 values with the X86 FP stack. ----
1579 /// Similarly, MVT::v2i64 turns into 4 MVT::i32 values with both PPC and X86. ----
1580 /// ----
1581 /// This method returns the number of registers needed, and the VT for each ----
1582 /// register. It also returns the VT and quantity of the intermediate values ----
1583 /// before they are promoted/expanded. ----
1584 unsigned TargetLoweringBase::getVectorTypeBreakdown(LLVMContext &Context, 0
1585 EVT VT, EVT &IntermediateVT, ----
1586 unsigned &NumIntermediates, ----
1587 MVT &RegisterVT) const { ----
1588 ElementCount EltCnt = VT.getVectorElementCount(); 0
1589 ----
1590 // If there is a wider vector type with the same element type as this one, ----
1591 // or a promoted vector type that has the same number of elements which ----
1592 // are wider, then we should convert to that legal vector type. ----
1593 // This handles things like <2 x float> -> <4 x float> and ----
1594 // <4 x i1> -> <4 x i32>. ----
1595 LegalizeTypeAction TA = getTypeAction(Context, VT); 0
1596 if (!EltCnt.isScalar() && 0
1597 (TA == TypeWidenVector || TA == TypePromoteInteger)) { 0
1598 EVT RegisterEVT = getTypeToTransformTo(Context, VT); 0
1599 if (isTypeLegal(RegisterEVT)) { 0
1600 IntermediateVT = RegisterEVT; 0
1601 RegisterVT = RegisterEVT.getSimpleVT(); 0
1602 NumIntermediates = 1; 0
1603 return 1; 0
1604 } ----
1605 } ----
1606 ----
1607 // Figure out the right, legal destination reg to copy into. ----
1608 EVT EltTy = VT.getVectorElementType(); 0
1609 ----
1610 unsigned NumVectorRegs = 1; 0
1611 ----
1612 // Scalable vectors cannot be scalarized, so handle the legalisation of the ----
1613 // types like done elsewhere in SelectionDAG. ----
1614 if (EltCnt.isScalable()) { 0
1615 LegalizeKind LK; 0
1616 EVT PartVT = VT; 0
1617 do { ----
1618 // Iterate until we've found a legal (part) type to hold VT. ----
1619 LK = getTypeConversion(Context, PartVT); 0
1620 PartVT = LK.second; 0
1621 } while (LK.first != TypeLegal); 0
1622 ----
1623 if (!PartVT.isVector()) { 0
1624 report_fatal_error( 0
1625 "Don't know how to legalize this scalable vector type"); ----
1626 } ----
1627 ----
1628 NumIntermediates = 0
1629 divideCeil(VT.getVectorElementCount().getKnownMinValue(), 0
1630 PartVT.getVectorElementCount().getKnownMinValue()); 0
1631 IntermediateVT = PartVT; 0
1632 RegisterVT = getRegisterType(Context, IntermediateVT); 0
1633 return NumIntermediates; 0
1634 } ----
1635 ----
1636 // FIXME: We don't support non-power-of-2-sized vectors for now. Ideally ----
1637 // we could break down into LHS/RHS like LegalizeDAG does. ----
1638 if (!isPowerOf2_32(EltCnt.getKnownMinValue())) { 0
1639 NumVectorRegs = EltCnt.getKnownMinValue(); 0
1640 EltCnt = ElementCount::getFixed(1); 0
1641 } ----
1642 ----
1643 // Divide the input until we get to a supported size. This will always ----
1644 // end with a scalar if the target doesn't support vectors. ----
1645 while (EltCnt.getKnownMinValue() > 1 && 0
1646 !isTypeLegal(EVT::getVectorVT(Context, EltTy, EltCnt))) { 0
1647 EltCnt = EltCnt.divideCoefficientBy(2); 0
1648 NumVectorRegs <<= 1; 0
1649 } ----
1650 ----
1651 NumIntermediates = NumVectorRegs; 0
1652 ----
1653 EVT NewVT = EVT::getVectorVT(Context, EltTy, EltCnt); 0
1654 if (!isTypeLegal(NewVT)) 0
1655 NewVT = EltTy; 0
1656 IntermediateVT = NewVT; 0
1657 ----
1658 MVT DestVT = getRegisterType(Context, NewVT); 0
1659 RegisterVT = DestVT; 0
1660 ----
1661 if (EVT(DestVT).bitsLT(NewVT)) { // Value is expanded, e.g. i64 -> i16. 0
1662 TypeSize NewVTSize = NewVT.getSizeInBits(); 0
1663 // Convert sizes such as i33 to i64. ----
1664 if (!llvm::has_single_bit(NewVTSize.getKnownMinValue())) 0
1665 NewVTSize = NewVTSize.coefficientNextPowerOf2(); 0
1666 return NumVectorRegs*(NewVTSize/DestVT.getSizeInBits()); 0
1667 } ----
1668 ----
1669 // Otherwise, promotion or legal types use the same number of registers as ----
1670 // the vector decimated to the appropriate level. ----
1671 return NumVectorRegs; 0
1672 } ----
1673 ----
1674 bool TargetLoweringBase::isSuitableForJumpTable(const SwitchInst *SI, 0
1675 uint64_t NumCases, ----
1676 uint64_t Range, ----
1677 ProfileSummaryInfo *PSI, ----
1678 BlockFrequencyInfo *BFI) const { ----
1679 // FIXME: This function check the maximum table size and density, but the ----
1680 // minimum size is not checked. It would be nice if the minimum size is ----
1681 // also combined within this function. Currently, the minimum size check is ----
1682 // performed in findJumpTable() in SelectionDAGBuiler and ----
1683 // getEstimatedNumberOfCaseClusters() in BasicTTIImpl. ----
1684 const bool OptForSize = ----
1685 SI->getParent()->getParent()->hasOptSize() || 0
1686 llvm::shouldOptimizeForSize(SI->getParent(), PSI, BFI); 0
1687 const unsigned MinDensity = getMinimumJumpTableDensity(OptForSize); 0
1688 const unsigned MaxJumpTableSize = getMaximumJumpTableSize(); 0
1689 ----
1690 // Check whether the number of cases is small enough and ----
1691 // the range is dense enough for a jump table. ----
1692 return (OptForSize || Range <= MaxJumpTableSize) && 0
1693 (NumCases * 100 >= Range * MinDensity); 0
1694 } ----

1696 MVT TargetLoweringBase::getPreferredSwitchConditionType(LLVMContext &Context, 0

1698 return getRegisterType(Context, ConditionVT); 0
1699 } ----

1762 bool TargetLoweringBase::allowsMemoryAccessForAlignment( 0
1763 LLVMContext &Context, const DataLayout &DL, EVT VT, unsigned AddrSpace, ----
1764 Align Alignment, MachineMemOperand::Flags Flags, unsigned *Fast) const { ----
1765 // Check if the specified alignment is sufficient based on the data layout. ----
1766 // TODO: While using the data layout works in practice, a better solution ----
1767 // would be to implement this check directly (make this a virtual function). ----
1768 // For example, the ABI alignment may change based on software platform while ----
1769 // this function should only be affected by hardware implementation. ----
1770 Type *Ty = VT.getTypeForEVT(Context); 0
1771 if (VT.isZeroSized() || Alignment >= DL.getABITypeAlign(Ty)) { 0
1772 // Assume that an access that meets the ABI-specified alignment is fast. ----
1773 if (Fast != nullptr) 0
1774 *Fast = 1; 0
1775 return true; 0
1776 } ----
1777 ----
1778 // This is a misaligned access. ----
1779 return allowsMisalignedMemoryAccesses(VT, AddrSpace, Alignment, Flags, Fast); 0
1780 } ----

1787 } ----

1898 Value * ----
1899 TargetLoweringBase::getDefaultSafeStackPointerLocation(IRBuilderBase &IRB, 0
1900 bool UseTLS) const { ----
1901 // compiler-rt provides a variable with a magic name. Targets that do not ----
1902 // link with compiler-rt may also provide such a variable. ----
1903 Module *M = IRB.GetInsertBlock()->getParent()->getParent(); 0
1904 const char *UnsafeStackPtrVar = "__safestack_unsafe_stack_ptr"; 0
1905 auto UnsafeStackPtr = ----
1906 dyn_cast_or_null(M->getNamedValue(UnsafeStackPtrVar)); 0
1907 ----
1908 Type *StackPtrTy = Type::getInt8PtrTy(M->getContext()); 0
1909 ----
1910 if (!UnsafeStackPtr) { 0
1911 auto TLSModel = UseTLS ? 0
1912 GlobalValue::InitialExecTLSModel : ----
1913 GlobalValue::NotThreadLocal; ----
1914 // The global variable is not defined yet, define it ourselves. ----
1915 // We use the initial-exec TLS model because we do not support the ----
1916 // variable living anywhere other than in the main executable. ----
1917 UnsafeStackPtr = new GlobalVariable( 0
1918 *M, StackPtrTy, false, GlobalValue::ExternalLinkage, nullptr, ----
1919 UnsafeStackPtrVar, nullptr, TLSModel); 0
1920 } else { ----
1921 // The variable exists, check its type and attributes. ----
1922 if (UnsafeStackPtr->getValueType() != StackPtrTy) 0
1923 report_fatal_error(Twine(UnsafeStackPtrVar) + " must have void* type"); 0
1924 if (UseTLS != UnsafeStackPtr->isThreadLocal()) 0
1925 report_fatal_error(Twine(UnsafeStackPtrVar) + " must " + 0
1926 (UseTLS ? "" : "not ") + "be thread-local"); 0
1927 } ----
1928 return UnsafeStackPtr; 0
1929 } ----
1930 ----
1931 Value * ----
1932 TargetLoweringBase::getSafeStackPointerLocation(IRBuilderBase &IRB) const { 0
1933 if (!TM.getTargetTriple().isAndroid()) 0
1934 return getDefaultSafeStackPointerLocation(IRB, true); 0
1935 ----
1936 // Android provides a libc function to retrieve the address of the current ----
1937 // thread's unsafe stack pointer. ----
1938 Module *M = IRB.GetInsertBlock()->getParent()->getParent(); 0
1939 Type *StackPtrTy = Type::getInt8PtrTy(M->getContext()); 0
1940 FunctionCallee Fn = M->getOrInsertFunction("__safestack_pointer_address", 0
1941 StackPtrTy->getPointerTo(0)); 0
1942 return IRB.CreateCall(Fn); 0
1943 } ----

1948 ----
1949 /// isLegalAddressingMode - Return true if the addressing mode represented ----
1950 /// by AM is legal for this target, for a load/store of the specified type. ----
1951 bool TargetLoweringBase::isLegalAddressingMode(const DataLayout &DL, 0
1952 const AddrMode &AM, Type *Ty, ----
1953 unsigned AS, Instruction *I) const { ----
1954 // The default implementation of this implements a conservative RISCy, r+r and ----
1955 // r+i addr mode. ----
1956 ----
1957 // Allows a sign-extended 16-bit immediate field. ----
1958 if (AM.BaseOffs <= -(1LL << 16) || AM.BaseOffs >= (1LL << 16)-1) 0
1959 return false; 0
1960 ----
1961 // No global is ever allowed as a base. ----
1962 if (AM.BaseGV) 0
1963 return false; 0
1964 ----
1965 // Only support r+r, ----
1966 switch (AM.Scale) { 0
1967 case 0: // "r+i" or just "i", depending on HasBaseReg. 0
1968 break; 0
1969 case 1: 0
1970 if (AM.HasBaseReg && AM.BaseOffs) // "r+r+i" is not allowed. 0
1971 return false; 0
1972 // Otherwise we have r+r or r+i. ----
1973 break; 0
1974 case 2: 0
1975 if (AM.HasBaseReg || AM.BaseOffs) // 2*r+r or 2*r+i is not allowed. 0
1976 return false; 0
1977 // Allow 2*r as r+r. ----
1978 break; 0
1979 default: // Don't allow n * r 0
1980 return false; 0
1981 } ----
1982 ----
1983 return true; 0
1984 } ----

1993 if (getTargetMachine().getTargetTriple().isOSOpenBSD()) { 0
1994 Module &M = *IRB.GetInsertBlock()->getParent()->getParent(); 0
1995 PointerType *PtrTy = Type::getInt8PtrTy(M.getContext()); 0
1996 Constant *C = M.getOrInsertGlobal("__guard_local", PtrTy); 0
1997 if (GlobalVariable *G = dyn_cast_or_null(C)) 0
1998 G->setVisibility(GlobalValue::HiddenVisibility); 0
1999 return C; 0
2000 } ----
2001 return nullptr; 0
2002 } ----

2070 /// Get the reciprocal estimate attribute string for a function that will ----
2071 /// override the target defaults. ----
2072 static StringRef getRecipEstimateForFunc(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
2073 const Function &F = MF.getFunction(); 0
2074 return F.getFnAttribute("reciprocal-estimates").getValueAsString(); 0
2075 } ----
2076 ----
2077 /// Construct a string for the given reciprocal operation of the given type. ----
2078 /// This string should match the corresponding option to the front-end's ----
2079 /// "-mrecip" flag assuming those strings have been passed through in an ----
2080 /// attribute string. For example, "vec-divf" for a division of a vXf32. ----
2081 static std::string getReciprocalOpName(bool IsSqrt, EVT VT) { 0
2082 std::string Name = VT.isVector() ? "vec-" : ""; 0
2083 ----
2084 Name += IsSqrt ? "sqrt" : "div"; 0
2085 ----
2086 // TODO: Handle other float types? ----
2087 if (VT.getScalarType() == MVT::f64) { 0
2088 Name += "d"; 0
2089 } else if (VT.getScalarType() == MVT::f16) { 0
2090 Name += "h"; 0

2360 // GlobalISel Hooks ----

2362 ----
2363 bool TargetLoweringBase::shouldLocalize(const MachineInstr &MI, 0
2364 const TargetTransformInfo *TTI) const { ----
2365 auto &MF = *MI.getMF(); 0
2366 auto &MRI = MF.getRegInfo(); 0
2367 // Assuming a spill and reload of a value has a cost of 1 instruction each, ----
2368 // this helper function computes the maximum number of uses we should consider ----
2369 // for remat. E.g. on arm64 global addresses take 2 insts to materialize. We ----
2370 // break even in terms of code size when the original MI has 2 users vs ----
2371 // choosing to potentially spill. Any more than 2 users we we have a net code ----
2372 // size increase. This doesn't take into account register pressure though. ----
2373 auto maxUses = [](unsigned RematCost) { 0
2374 // A cost of 1 means remats are basically free. ----
2375 if (RematCost == 1) 0
2376 return std::numeric_limits::max(); 0
2377 if (RematCost == 2) 0
2378 return 2U; 0
2379 ----
2380 // Remat is too expensive, only sink if there's one user. ----
2381 if (RematCost > 2) 0
2382 return 1U; 0
2383 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected remat cost"); 0
2384 }; ----
2385 ----
2386 switch (MI.getOpcode()) { 0
2387 default: 0
2388 return false; 0
2389 // Constants-like instructions should be close to their users. ----
2390 // We don't want long live-ranges for them. ----
2391 case TargetOpcode::G_CONSTANT: 0
2392 case TargetOpcode::G_FCONSTANT: ----
2393 case TargetOpcode::G_FRAME_INDEX: ----
2394 case TargetOpcode::G_INTTOPTR: ----
2395 return true; 0
2396 case TargetOpcode::G_GLOBAL_VALUE: { 0
2397 unsigned RematCost = TTI->getGISelRematGlobalCost(); 0
2398 Register Reg = MI.getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
2399 unsigned MaxUses = maxUses(RematCost); 0
2400 if (MaxUses == UINT_MAX) 0
2401 return true; // Remats are "free" so always localize. 0
2402 return MRI.hasAtMostUserInstrs(Reg, MaxUses); 0
2403 } ----
2404 } ----
2405 } ----
